\subsection*{Problem 1}

\begin{problem}
\textbf{Background:}
The dynamics of a reaction coordinate $q(t)$ in protein folding can be described by the Generalized Langevin Equation (GLE), which accounts for memory effects. The GLE for an overdamped system (where inertial effects are negligible, $m \to 0$) in the absence of an external potential ($U(q)=0$) is characterized by a friction memory kernel $\Gamma(t)$. This kernel is often well-approximated by a multi-exponential function:
$$ \Gamma(t) = \sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{\gamma_i}{\tau_i} e^{-t/\tau_i} $$
where $\gamma_i$ are friction coefficients and $\tau_i$ are characteristic memory times. For many fast-folding proteins, these parameters exhibit a hierarchical structure, meaning that consecutive memory times and friction coefficients are related by constant ratios:
$$ \tau_i = \tau_1 c^{i-1} \quad \text{and} \quad \gamma_i = \gamma_1 d^{i-1} $$
Here, $\tau_1$ and $\gamma_1$ are the shortest memory time and its corresponding friction coefficient, respectively, and $c$ and $d$ are constants. It has been observed that for $c > d > 1$, this multi-exponential kernel approximates a power-law behavior $\Gamma(t) \propto t^{-\alpha_{\rm{sub}}}$ over an intermediate time range. In this regime, the mean squared displacement (MSD), defined as $C_{\rm{MSD}}(t) = \langle (q(t) - q(0))^2 \rangle$, also exhibits a subdiffusive scaling $C_{\rm{MSD}}(t) \propto t^{\alpha_{\rm{sub}}}$. For a sum of exponentials with widely separated time scales, the behavior of the sum at a given time $t$ is often dominated by the exponential term whose characteristic time $\tau_i$ is approximately equal to $t$.

\textbf{Task:}
Assuming that the power-law behavior of $\Gamma(t)$ is primarily determined by the term in the sum where the memory time $\tau_i$ is approximately equal to the observation time $t$, derive the expression for the subdiffusive scaling exponent $\alpha_{\rm{sub}}$ in terms of $c$ and $d$.

\end{problem}

